You&#39;re currently looking for the max element between each value and it&#39;s next, so at the end you just get the max between the last value and the previous one

To find the max, get the max between the current value and the max you&#39;ve got so far. You can initialize your `max` to the first value and start iterate at the second (`i=1`) value

    public static int maximizeSum(int[] nums) {
        int max = nums[0];
        for(int i=1; i&lt;nums.length ; i++){
            max = Math.max(nums[i], max);
        }
        return max;
    }

Your algorithm is incorrect.

You are simply evaluating the maximum of every two elements.  
The last two are _1_ and _7_, thus _max_ is assigned _7_.

Check _max_ before assigning the value.

```java
public static int maximizeSum(int[] nums) {
    int max = nums[0], value;
    for(int i=0; i&lt;nums.length - 1; i++){
        value = Math.max(nums[i],nums[i+1]);
        if (value &gt; max) max = value;
    }
    return max;
}
```

Another way to do this is one item at a time, as opposed to every two.

```java
int max = nums[0];
for (int value : nums) {
    if (value &gt; max) max = value;
}
return max;
```

Additionally, you can use the _Collections#max_ method, although you&#39;d need to use an _Integer_ array, and not an _int_ array.

```java
Collections.max(Arrays.asList(nums));
```

